==Controversy== As in other places, there has been controversy surrounding plans to bring Street View to various Asian countries.
In [[Israel]], there have been concerns that introducing the service could increase the risk of terrorism to which the region is prone.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2011/feb/22/business/la-fi-google-israel-20110222|title=Some in Israel warn against Google Street View|last=Guynn|first=Jessica|date=February 22, 2011|work=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=March 17, 2011}}</ref>
In [[India]], the Government rejected Google Street View. Official sources said the rejection came after a detailed analysis by security agencies and defense forces which feel that allowing Google to cover India would compromise country’s security interest. Security establishments became wary of allowing such image capturing given that planning for the 2008 terrorist attacks in Mumbai is believed to have involved photographic reconnaissance of targets by Pakistani American David Coleman Headley. The Indian Government had plans to talk about Google street view in India, but in March 2018 Government of India finally rejected the Google Street view plan citing that this will compromise the country's security as India is constantly targeted by terrorist groups from Pakistan, especially in Kashmir valley.
Google had to reshoot all images in Japan because the camera cars that took the original photographs were originally too high, leading to [[Google Street View privacy concerns|privacy concerns]]. Japanese houses are generally built quite close to the road. Roads are also narrow, often without pavements. Such factors led to privacy concerns with the original photographs.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/8049490.stm|title=Street View under fire in Japan|date=May 14, 2009|work=BBC|accessdate=March 17, 2011|location=UK}}</ref>
Police in [[South Korea]] raided offices in that country in order to determine if Street View was legal.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.cnet.com/8301-1009_3-20013156-83.html|title=South Korea raids Google over Street View|last=Whitney|first=Lance|date=August 10, 2010|work=CNet News|accessdate=March 17, 2011}}</ref>
In 2013, people in Tambon Sa-iap village, [[Song District]] in Phrae Province, Thailand, mistakenly believed that the Street View car was surveying the village for the [[NIMBY|unwanted]] [[Kaeng Suea Ten Dam]] project and blocked it, not allowing it to take photographs. They also arrested the driver and interrogated him to determine if he was working for the dam project. He was released after swearing on the [[Buddha]] that his work was not related to the dam project. After confirming his story, the village's leaders apologized for the misunderstanding.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bangkokpost.com/learning/easy/364735/what-google-street-view-worker-stopped-for-spying|title=What's Google? "Street View" worker stopped for spying|first=Terry|last=Fredrickson|date=August 15, 2013|accessdate=September 1, 2014|work=[[Bangkok Post]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2013/aug/15/thai-arrest-google-street-view|title=Thai villagers make citizens' arrest of Google Street View driver|date=August 15, 2013|accessdate=September 1, 2014|work=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref>
